{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13975"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13975"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.15,0.03,0.38,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13975"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38758"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of increasing colicky abdominal pain and distention. She feels nauseated and has been vomiting. She has experienced several episodes of right-sided abdominal pain over the last few months, each settling after a few days. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She does not drink alcohol or smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 116/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her BMI is 22 kg/m2. Her abdomen is uniformly distended but soft to palpation, with increased tinkling bowel sounds. No masses or hernias are identified. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her small bowel obstruction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the colon","Adhesions","Hernia","Gallstone ileus","Appendix mucocele"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features of small bowel obstruction. The CT scan shows dilated loops of small bowel and a well-encapsulated cystic mass with wall calcification in the right iliac fossa, characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendix mucocele\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). The recurrent right-sided abdominal pain over several months is consistent with intermittent partial obstruction from this lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdhesions\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common cause of small bowel obstruction (60% of cases), but this patient has no history of previous abdominal surgery, making adhesions unlikely as the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHernia\u003C/strong\u003E is the second most common cause of small bowel obstruction (15% of cases). However, physical examination did not reveal any hernias, and the patient\u0027s low BMI would make detection of a hernia relatively straightforward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the colon\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with large bowel obstruction rather than small bowel obstruction, unless there is peritoneal carcinomatosis. The CT appearance is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with mechanical small bowel obstruction in elderly patients with a history of gallstone disease. CT would show pneumobilia and a large gallstone in the small bowel, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppendiceal mucocele is a rare condition characterised by abnormal accumulation of mucus causing dilatation of the appendiceal lumen. While most are benign, they can cause obstruction through mass effect or adhesions. Surgical resection is typically required, with careful handling to prevent rupture and subsequent pseudomyxoma peritonei.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Appendiceal mucocele is a rare cause of small bowel obstruction characterised by mucus-filled dilatation of the appendix.","CT findings of appendiceal mucocele include a well-encapsulated cystic mass with wall calcification in the right iliac fossa.","Common causes of small bowel obstruction include adhesions (60%) and hernias (15%), but unusual causes must be considered in patients without previous surgery."],"references":["Pal NL, Panandiker SD, Katiyar G, et al  Unusual causes of Small bowel obstruction: a review of the literature and revisited cross-sectional imaging checklist Emerg Radiol. 2024; 31:733-48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13975"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20868"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21549"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20868"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage